His struggles echoed within me, a dissonance that would not abate until I chanced upon his mother, a woman whose gaze was as foreign as the language she spoke - a language that hung in the air like an invisible veil, an impenetrable barrier that separated her from the world around her. It was in that moment, amidst the silence of unspoken comprehension, that the truth began to reveal itself: Adrian's troubles lay not in his ability to read, but in his unfamiliarity with the English alphabet, a fundamental building block of literacy that had been withheld from him.

This story I recount, a testament to the insidious nature of the language barrier that pervades our schools, particularly in a state like California, where the multiplicity of tongues and cultures seems to strain against the fabric of our collective understanding. It is a problem that seeks to confound us, to make us doubt our assumptions and our solutions. We are wont to think that language is a fixed entity, a clearly defined construct that can be learned and mastered with ease. But it is not so. For Adrian, the solution lay in the simplest of measures: a tutor's patient hand guiding him through the labyrinth of the alphabet, the gentle coaxing of sounds and meanings from the darkness. Yet for those children who are doubly bereft, those who speak little or no English, the answer is more complex, a Gordian knot that can only be unraveled through a multifaceted approach.

The dual language system, a program that seeks to nurture the bilingual minds of our children, is often met with skepticism and trepidation. We are told that it is a costly endeavor, that it will drain resources and yield little in return. But I would counter that this is a misconception, a false narrative that arises from a lack of understanding. The evidence suggests otherwise: children in two-way bilingual education programs have been shown to outperform their peers academically. It is not a panacea, but a key that can unlock the doors of understanding for all our children, regardless of their linguistic heritage.

So how do we proceed? Do we demand that our teachers be bilingual? No, that would be a foolhardy expectation, one that would precipitate a crisis of proportions we cannot imagine. But we can - and must - provide the necessary tools to bridge the chasm of language. We can employ special aids, tutors, or whatever moniker we choose, who are fluent in multiple tongues. We can create an environment that values and celebrates the diversity of our children's language backgrounds, an environment that is as inclusive as it is supportive. In this way, we can begin to chip away at the obstacle of language, to create a future where every child has the opportunity to flourish, to read, to write, and to speak with confidence and precision.

In the twilight of our earliest years, a presence looms, a force beyond our mortal grasp. Some seek solace in the hallowed halls of Sunday school, while others tread the dusty paths of ancient temples, or probe the recesses of their own minds for answers. Many surrender to the faiths bequeathed to them by their forebears, their conviction born of tradition and upbringing. Others, however, reject the edifice of dogma, scorning the notion of a transcendent realm beyond the confines of their own self-absorbed universe. We oscillate between disparate value systems, our spiritual compasses quivering like a compass needle in the void, as we strive to chart a course through the darkness.

"A cardinal," my father said, his voice a low, measured rumble, as we sat on the creaking porch, the rain drumming a relentless beat on the tin roof above. The gutters groaned, overflowing with the deluge, drowning the parched plants along the porch's edge. His eyes, sunken and haunted, seemed to stare into some distant realm, a mixture of searching and remembrance. Months of illness had leached the vitality from his frame, leaving him gaunt and spectral. His hair, once a rich mane, now hung sparse and lifeless. I felt a creeping dread, a sense of irreparable loss, as I watched him struggle to keep his gaze fixed on the rain-soaked world beyond us. I knew that speaking of it would only amplify the ache within us both, so I contented myself with a tentative touch, moving my chair closer to his, and joining him in his somber contemplation.

My father's passing came in December, five days shy of my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation, a cruel jest of modern medicine, had prolonged his suffering, rendering him a shadow of his former self. What purpose did this serve, I wondered, as I lay alone in the dark, the silence a heavy shroud upon me. I did not pray, for if a God existed, I had long since abandoned any notion that He listened to my pleas. The thought was a cold comfort, a bleak acknowledgment of the abyss that yawned between us.

I had not wished to witness his final passage, to behold the last flicker of life ebbing from his frame. I could not bear to watch the man who had given me life slip into the void. I wanted to recall him in all his vibrant, unbroken glory, not in the fragile, fading shell that now lay before me. Besides, I knew him better than any, better than his family, better than anyone. He would not have wanted me to be a bystander to his departure, a mere spectator to the end of his journey. I curled into a fetal ball, wrapping myself in the shroud of my own grief, waiting for the news that would shatter me.

The silence was my only companion, a silence that wrapped itself around me like a shroud, unbroken and unbroken. No word came, no solace, no comfort. Only the stillness, and the darkness, and the crushing weight of my own despair.

In a dissonant union of terms, the Gothic novel embodies the oxymoronic conjunction of the ancient and the modern, an incongruity that Ian Watt astutely observes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This literary mode has been derided and extolled, its profundity questioned and its capacity for evoking the 'terrible sublime' lauded by some (Burke). The earliest exemplar of the Gothic novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, drew upon the ancient romance and the modern novel to forge a new idiom, a synthesis of theater and nature. In this work, Walpole wove together the tattered threads of medieval Gothic theater, architecture, and tradition, creating a tapestry that would captivate and confound readers for generations to come. At the time of its publication, the term 'Gothic' was a polyvalent label, applied to disparate peoples, styles, and epochs. It was a term freighted with connotations of antiquity and unsophistication, an anachronism in the face of the modernity that was rapidly transforming the world.

Yet it was precisely this union of the archaic and the modern that allowed the Gothic novel to endure, its timelessness a testament to its capacity to transcend the boundaries of time and place. As the reader is transported to a world both familiar and strange, the novel's Gothic past is idealized and romanticized, its chivalric ideals and manners casting a long shadow over the present. In The Castle of Otranto, Walpole's use of chivalric concepts and mannerisms serves as a poignant reminder of a bygone era, an era in which honor, bravery, and competence were the hallmarks of a true knight. This nostalgia for a vanished world was not merely a sentimental exercise, but a cri de coeur, a lament for the passing of a moral order that Walpole saw as being rapidly eroded in his own time.

In the midst of a tumultuous era, Walpole's writing was a cry of despair, a lament for the loss of a world that seemed to be slipping away from him. His characters, including the enigmatic Frederic, embody the ideals of chivalry with a fervor that is both admirable and excessive. Frederic, a prince of unyielding virtue, has suffered the slings and arrows of outrageous fortune, and his very existence is a testament to the power of honor and courage in the face of adversity. His description is a litany of chivalric virtues: a prince, a sufferer, a man of unwavering commitment to his principles. And yet, this idealized figure is also a product of excess, a Gothic trope that would come to define the genre. In Frederic, we see the apotheosis of the gallant and courteous knight, a figure that would haunt the pages of the Gothic novel for generations to come.

The labyrinthine threads of commerce weave together in an intricate dance, each strand a vital link in the unyielding chain that binds the customer to the raw material, and from thence to the product that satisfies their most primal needs. Supply chain management, a term coined by the sibylline Keith Oliver in 1982, is the unseen hand that governs this odyssey, a conjurer of efficiencies and a weaver of bespoke solutions. It is the master plan that orchestrates the symphony of production, supply, and distribution, a delicate ballet of movement and tempo.

Six discrete elements comprise the nucleus of this grand endeavor: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These pillars, sturdy and unyielding, support the weight of the supply chain, providing a foundation upon which the edifice of customer satisfaction is built. The managers of commerce, wise and foresighted, employ these six elements to craft a narrative of service that is at once swift, efficient, and responsive to the whims of the market.

Production, the inaugural step in this grand procession, is the fertile soil in which the seeds of success are sown. It is here that the managers of industry must attune themselves to the rhythm of the market, listening to the whispers of the customer's demand, and responding with products that are at once relevant and desirable. The market, a capricious and mercurial force, holds sway over the production process, guiding the manager's hand as they chart the course of their endeavors.

As the manager navigates the treacherous waters of production, they must also consider the complexities of location, that most critical of variables. Where will the product be manufactured? At which plant will it be crafted, and with what degree of precision and quality? The manager must weigh the competing demands of volume and satisfaction, ever mindful of the customer's insatiable hunger for value and convenience.

The schedule of workloads and the maintenance of equipment are also crucial considerations, for in the realm of production, every detail is a thread in the intricate tapestry of commerce. A misstep, a miscalculation, can prove costly in the long run, a lesson learned by those who have walked the hallowed halls of retail, where the giants of commerce, Wal-Mart and Target, have honed their craft through the meticulous attention to detail and the relentless pursuit of excellence.

Supply, the second pillar of this grand edifice, is the strategic art of discerning the core capabilities of a facility and forging alliances with partners who share a common vision. A manager must navigate the labyrinth of divisions, each with its unique strengths and specialties, and decide which path to follow, which partnerships to forge, and which opportunities to seize. And in this dance of supply, velocity is the holy grail, the elusive goal of providing quality, flexibility, and cost-effectiveness in equal measure.

The faded words on the cardboard sign above Ellen's head seemed to bleed into the dusty street, a macabre message scrawled in Sharpie: "Hitler is alive in Burma". The stark phrase hung like a challenge in the sweltering air, a jarring reminder of the darkness that lurked beneath the surface of this troubled land. Myanmar, a Southeast Asian country shrouded in the shadows of a tyrannical regime, had been ruled by the iron fist of a militant junta since the coup that seized power in 1962. The whispered rumors of a Saffron Revolution, born from the ash of public protests in 2007, spoke of a nation torn asunder by the monastic robes of its people, and the bloodlust of those who would seek to silence them.

It began with whispers, a gentle murmur of dissent that grew into a roar, as the monks, those revered guardians of the faith, took to the streets to demand justice. Foreign eyes, those of Kenji Nagai, a Japanese photojournalist, had witnessed the horrors of that conflict, and paid the ultimate price for his bravery. His death, like the countless others, was a testament to the unyielding resolve of those who sought to silence the voices of the people. Colonel Hla Win, a man who had defected from the very ranks of the junta, spoke of a toll that far exceeded the official count, a grim tally that spoke of a nation lost to madness and despair.

But this is a story that has been told before, in the dusty tomes of history, where the empires of old rose and fell, their leaders driven by a lust for power, a hunger that knew no bounds. The Romans, those gods-ordained rulers, had decreed their dominance over their people, while in Japan, the emperor was believed to be a deity, sent to guide his people to greatness through the blessings of the divine. And in our own time, the echoes of a bygone era whispered through the halls of power, as a president, a man with a god-complex, held court with the leaders of a world that seemed to have lost its way.

In the annals of time, there are those who bear witness to the horrors of human nature: Tiananmen Square, where the ghosts of the dead still lingered, their numbers lost to the sands of time; the Rwandan genocide, a systematic slaughter of innocents, driven by the primal urges of hate and fear; and the Third Reich, a nightmare of unimaginable proportions, where the very fabric of humanity was torn asunder by the madness of a single man. These are the echoes of a world in chaos, a world that seems to be forever lost in the darkness of its own making.

The shadow of Duke Ellington looms large over the jazz landscape, his legacy an unyielding testament to the enduring power of creative vision. It is a testament forged in the crucible of time, tempered by the fires of innovation and the patient shaping of his orchestra. The piano, an instrument that could be as subtle as a summer breeze or as piercing as a winter storm, played its part in the compositions chosen for this exercise, but it was Ellington's genius as a composer that truly defined his art. He crafted frameworks within which his musicians could unfurl like a blooming flower, their individual petals of sound unfolding in a tapestry of rich and complex beauty. And yet, he was not averse to tightly coiled phrases, phrases that coiled around the essence of his players like a snake around its prey, coaxing forth the essence of their unique styles.

The Creole Love Call, an early masterpiece, stands as a testament to Ellington's willingness to experiment with the very fabric of sound. In this 12-bar blues, the human voice was elevated to an instrument of the highest order, its timbre weaving in and out of the reeds like a summer mist. The piece is a slow, deliberate dance, its six choruses unfolding like the petals of a flower. In the first, the voice and reeds engage in a call and response, the voice beginning smooth as silk, gradually roughening like the bark of a tree. The second chorus revolves around a muted trumpet, its solo a languid elaboration of the melody, replete with the sweet, mournful tones of the blue note.

The third chorus is a clarinet's lament, its sweeping phrases backed by a piano that trembles like a leaf in the autumn wind. The fourth chorus, a full-bodied echo of the first, sees the brass and reed sections engaging in a call and response, their voices entwined like the branches of a ancient tree. The fifth chorus is a climactic crescendo, the reeds now the initiators of the call, their voices soaring in the high register as the brass and rhythm sections provide a syncopated counterpoint. And in the final chorus, the voice assumes the "growl" technique, soloing like an instrument, its sound a primal howl of joy and release.

In Hot and Bothered, a piece recorded a year later, Ellington's mastery of orchestration is on full display, his ear for tone color guiding the intricate dance of sound. A call and response phrase between Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing is a masterclass in the marriage of vocal and instrumental elements, the two sounds blending together like the colors of a sunset on a summer's day. And in It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), Ellington's use of Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a stalwart of his orchestra, is a testament to his ability to coax the very best from his musicians, the muted trombone introducing the melody with a subtle, seductive elegance.

The yearning had been a constant companion, a gnawing emptiness that refused to be sated. It had begun to take hold when she was a girl, a tender sprout of adolescence pushing its way up through the earth of her soul. Three years had passed, and the ache remained, a stubborn thorn that refused to be plucked. Her desire had shifted, from a thing to a person, yet the void within her remained unfulfilled. The faces of boys had crossed her path, each one a pale imitation of what she sought, and she had watched them with a detached curiosity, a stranger observing the antics of the oblivious.

She had questioned herself, pored over the mysteries of her own heart, seeking answers that remained elusive. Theories had been proposed, whispered in the darkness of her mind, but they were feeble attempts to grasp the ungraspable. She had lived, a cipher of uncertainty, suspended between the poles of longing and despair.

But this was not a day like any other. The house, a sanctuary of calm and tranquility, was rent asunder by the sound of her mother's cry. A scream, a raw and anguished cry, cut through the stillness like a knife. She ran, her feet pounding the floor, her heart racing with a mixture of fear and dread. The kitchen, a place of warmth and comfort, was now a scene of chaos and distress.

Her mother lay on the floor, her face twisted in a grimace of pain, her voice a barely audible whisper. "Ow...sweet...take me to the hospital." The words were torn from her lips, a desperate plea that shook the daughter to her core. She rushed to her side, her hand reaching out to still the turmoil within her. "Mom, what's wrong?" she asked, her voice shaking with concern. The answer was a hasty series of instructions, a directions to the car, and the daughter's resolve was set. She lifted her mother, her strength and resolve mingling with her worry and fear.

The hospital loomed before them, a bastion of sterility and suffering. The scent of disinfectant and sickness hung in the air, a noxious cloud that clung to the skin. But she pushed it aside, her mind focused on the task at hand. She carried her mother, a fragile, broken thing, to the reception desk, her voice rising above the din of the waiting room. "Help! My mother needs attention!" The faces turned, a blur of concern and compassion, and a wheelchair was produced, a makeshift cradle for her mother's broken body.

The doctors came, their faces a blur of efficiency and expertise, and her mother was whisked away, a fragile leaf on the wind. She was left to wait, a sentinel of worry, her heart heavy with the weight of her mother's pain. The fall from the stool, a seemingly minor incident, had left her mother broken and battered. The stillness of the house had given way to chaos and confusion, and she was left to pick up the pieces, to try and make sense of the shattered world around her.

The dim lights of a distant world cast long shadows across the expanse of our understanding, yet the promise of the Mediterranean Diet beckons us forward like a siren's call.  Its adherents, a verdant host, feast upon the bounty of plant life - fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes - their tables spread with the trappings of a healthier existence.  They eschew the darkness of saturated fats, instead welcoming the golden glow of monounsaturated oils into their lives.  And in this quiet reverence for the land, they find solace in the gentle warmth of moderate alcohol, a reminder that even in excess, there is a fine line between indulgence and moderation.

The whispers of prior studies have long whispered of the Med Diet's protective benefits - a shield against the ravages of total and cardiovascular mortality, a gentle breeze that rustles the leaves of weight loss and low-density lipoprotein cholesterol.  Yet, a void had existed in our knowledge, a chasm that yawned wide and deep, unexplored and uncharted, where the mysteries of stroke and stroke mortality dwelled.  It is in this void that our study ventures forth, a lone traveler in the wilderness of data, seeking to illuminate the paths that lead to a healthier existence.

Our journey began with 74,886 women, a sisterhood bound together by the Nurses' Health Study, a vast and sprawling tapestry of 121,700 female nurses in 11 states.  Over six intervals, from 1984 to 2004, we computed the aMed diet score, a metric that sang the praises of their nutrient intake, their tables spread with the bounty of their self-reported "food frequency questionnaires."  And though the years went by, like autumn leaves rustling in the wind, more than 95% of these women remained steadfast, their participation a testament to the power of dedication and perseverance.

Their reports of heart disease, fatal heart disease, and stroke were confirmed by the cold, unforgiving light of medical records, hospital documents, and death certificates.  And where the records were scarce, we relied on the whispered rumors of probable cases, a shadowy realm where 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts dwelled.  We also calculated the body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use, a litany of factors that sought to confuse and mislead us.  But we stood firm, our gaze fixed on the horizon, as we adjusted for these confounders, our steps steady and resolute.

The Cox proportional-hazard modeling, a statistical cartographer, charted the course of our inquiry, its terrain marked by the aMed score and the risk of heart disease and stroke.  And in the end, our findings emerged like a dawn breaking over the horizon - the women who adhered to the Mediterranean Diet, their aMed diet score a beacon of hope, were at lower risk for both heart disease and stroke, their relative risk a mere 0.71, a testament to the power of a diet that honors the land and the body.

The darkness crept in like a thief in the night, stealing the very foundations of a nation's prosperity. It began in 2007, a year when the behemoths of American finance teetered on the precipice of collapse. Unemployment stalked the land like a specter, the housing market lay in shambles, and the once-mighty corporations, those titans of industry, were reduced to mere shadows of their former selves. And so, we are left to ponder: how did this catastrophe unfold, and how might we prevent its recurrence? The answer lies in the hubris of those who would guide the ship of state, their decisions driven by a reckless abandon that would have far-reaching consequences. They goaded the banks and financial institutions to peddle sub-prime loans to the unwary, to those who could ill afford them, into an economic landscape as fragile as a house of cards.

The machinery of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, those behemoths of the financial world, was coerced into buying and repackaging these toxic assets, creating a Frankenstein's monster of a financial system. And when the inevitable day of reckoning arrived, the banks found themselves bereft of capital, their reserves drained by the very chaos they had unleashed. The contagion spread, a cancer that would not be contained, infecting the very fabric of the economy.

The seeds of destruction were sown in 1999, a year of promise and hubris. The Clinton administration, driven by a lust for power and a desire to enhance their popularity, chose to ease lending restrictions, setting in motion a chain of events that would lead to a catastrophe of unimaginable proportions. Steven Holmes, a prophet of sorts, penned a prescient warning in the pages of the New York Times, "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton administration to expand mortgage loans among low- and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits." His words, a clarion call to beware, fell on deaf ears, and the consequences of their actions would be dire indeed. "But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s," he wrote, a prediction that would prove all too accurate.

The economic landscape was transformed by the proliferation of new and complex financial instruments, a veritable Tower of Babel that would eventually collapse under its own weight. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were the instruments of choice, weaving a web of debt that would ensnare the very fabric of the economy. The U.S. households and financial markets, drunk on the sweet nectar of easy credit, overextended themselves, leaving them vulnerable to the slightest tremors in the market. And when the housing bubble burst, the consequences were catastrophic. The top five U.S. investment banks reported a staggering $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, a sum that would haunt the nation for generations to come. Bear, Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold for a pittance, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to submit to a regimen of intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie, their coffers overflowing with mortgage debt, were placed under government control, a testament to the hubris of those who had brought about their downfall.

The stagnant air of exposition clings to the writer's words like the dry dust of a forgotten land.  It is the place where the narrative's wings beat listlessly, a monotone drone that threatens to lull the reader into a state of torpor, their eyes glazing over like the surface of a stagnant pool.  Dr. Merlin's fingers dance across the keyboard, her face a mask of frustration as she wrestles with the siren's song of Too Much Information.

Exposition, that seductive fiend, whispers sweet nothings in the writer's ear, urging them to dispense with the tedious details, to hasten the pace and reach the meat of the story.  But it is a deceitful guide, one that promises a quick escape from the tedium of character development, of atmosphere, of the slow unfolding of the narrative's tapestry.

The cardinal sin of exposition is to tell, rather than to show.  To dump the reader's lap with a veritable feast of facts and figures, leaving them to sort through the morass like a lost traveler in a desert.  In the cinema, it is the awkward exchange, the clunky exposition dump, where one character unloads their entire life story upon another, a cliche-ridden monologue that would put even the most patient viewer to sleep.  In fiction, it is the author's own telling hand that wields the pen of exposition, carving out great chunks of narrative with all the finesse of a hatchet.

Consider, for instance, a heroine whose life has been forever altered by the presence of a man.  We are told of their meeting, of their marriage, of his brutal and senseless murder.  But what of the man himself?  What of the love they shared, the laughter, the tears, the whispered promises in the dead of night?  To reduce their history to a mere paragraph, a cold recitation of facts, is to deny the reader the chance to feel the weight of his loss, to mourn his passing alongside the heroine.  It is to leave their emotions as dry and barren as the page itself.

A writer's task, then, is to breathe life into the bones of the narrative.  To flesh out the characters, to infuse them with the subtle nuances of speech and action, to allow the reader to glimpse the hidden recesses of their souls.  It is a labor of love, a slow and painstaking craft that requires patience, persistence, and a willingness to let the story unfold at its own pace.  For in the end, it is not the telling that matters, but the showing.  The meat of the story, not the bare bones.  The reader's participation, not their tolerance.

And so, the writer's hand hovers over the keyboard, poised to strike, ready to begin.  But the temptation to rush, to dispense with the tedious details, is ever-present, a siren's call that beckons them down a path of least resistance.  To indulge, and risk losing the reader in a sea of exposition, or to resist, and risk crafting a narrative that is lean, mean, and alive.  The choice, as ever, is theirs alone.

I watched the newscast from Columbus, Ohio, a city shrouded in the hush of morning's early light. The NBC 4 broadcast, carried on the thirteenth of August in the year of our reckoning, 2011, unfolded like a tapestry of violence and despair. The lead story, a disquieting tale of domestic carnage, spoke of a man named Shad Hostettler, his face twisted in a grim rictus, his eyes vacant as a doll's. They showed his mug shot, a fleeting glimpse into the abyss that had driven him to stab his wife, her name left unspoken, a forgotten cipher. The report was brief, a mere two minutes of airtime, as if the gravity of the act was too much to bear, a weight that threatened to consume the very fabric of the broadcast.

The next story, a somber account of a shooting in the Sharon Woods area, seemed to be devoured by the very shadows that shrouded it. Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old youth, lay critically injured, his fate hanging in the balance, a threadbare thread of hope suspended between life and death. The SWAT team moved in, a dark and impersonal force, their presence a stark reminder of the violence that lurked in every corner. I couldn't help but wonder if the news would have given the same attention to a similar tale if the victim had been a different hue, if the neighborhood had been a different shade of skin.

The news continued, a litany of violence and disregard, a litany of lives lost or forever changed. A gunshot hole marred the Med-Flight helicopter, a reminder of the randomness of violence, the ease with which it can strike. A .22 caliber bullet, fired from a rifle, had pierced the metal, leaving a trail of uncertainty in its wake. A five-thousand-dollar reward was offered for information leading to the shooter's capture, a fleeting promise of justice in a world that often seemed devoid of it.

The forecast, a brief interlude of tranquility, spoke of rain and thunderstorms to come, a respite from the darkness that had plagued the city. The temperatures, a mere afterthought, would hover in the mid to low eighties, a trivial concern in the face of the violence that had consumed the airwaves.

Another story, a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road, unfolded like a tired trop, a narrative of a dark-skinned black man, his features reduced to a mere caricature. He wore a hoodie, a symbol of anonymity, a cloak of invisibility. His height, a mere 6 feet tall, his weight, a paltry 150 pounds, seemed almost laughable, a grotesque parody of humanity. The news anchor's voice dripped with an almost cruel emphasis, as if the man's color was the only thing that mattered.

And then, like a whisper in the wind, a mention of Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas kingpin, his fate sealed in a 300-month sentence, a number that seemed to hold a certain je ne sais quoi, a certain gravity that the news anchor sought to convey. But what did it matter, really? Was it the length of the sentence, or the fact that he was a Hispanic man, a label that seemed to serve no purpose in the story? The news, a reflection of our collective soul, a soul that seems to shrug at the violence, the injustice, the disregard for life.

In the vast and unforgiving expanse of brotherhood, a bond forms, unyielding and unrelenting. Like a tempest, it sweeps through the souls of two men, leaving in its wake a tempest of emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty – a maelstrom of fervor that defies the tender mercies of reason. It is here, in the crucible of adversity, that the true mettle of this bond is tried, and the depths of their characters are laid bare. The cost of this union is a heavy one, a burden that must be shouldered by those who would walk this path. To gaze into the eyes of one's brother is to behold a reflection of oneself, unvarnished and unflinching – a mirror held up to the darkness that lies within.

In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers embark upon a journey through a lush, verdant landscape, their footsteps echoing through the stillness like the beat of a funeral drum. The air is thick with the weight of their emotions, as bitter disappointment struggles against the intense pride that threatens to consume them both. It is here, in this fevered moment, that the true nature of their bond is revealed, a tangled web of love and resentment that ultimately proves fatal for one of them. Through the eyes of the narrator, we are given a glimpse into the twisted world of the protagonist, a world in which the lines between good and evil are blurred, and the consequences of one's actions are writ large upon the landscape.

The protagonist's actions are a testament to the power of pride, a monolith of emotion that towers over his every waking moment. From the outset, he is driven by a sense of disappointment, a sense that his brother Doodle, crippled by a weak heart, is a constant reminder of all that he has lost. He had dreamed of a brother who could keep pace with him, a companion in the untamed wilderness of their youth. But Doodle's frailty shatters these dreams, leaving the protagonist to grapple with the darkness that lies within. His heart seethes with anger and resentment, a cauldron of emotions that threatens to boil over at any moment. And yet, it is in these moments of fury that we catch glimpses of a deeper love, a love that is both beautiful and terrible in its intensity. The protagonist's thoughts turn to the unthinkable – to suffocating the small child with a pillow – and yet, it is the simple, unguarded smile of his brother that stays his hand, a reminder of the love that lies at the heart of their bond. It is a love that flickers like a candle in the darkness, a fragile flame that threatens to be extinguished by the very emotions that seek to consume it.

The mind is a labyrinthine repository of unfathomable complexity, a vast and dark expanse of neural concatenation. As the epochs pass, so too do the metaphors that have been used to describe it, each one a faint echo of the truth, a fleeting glimpse of the abyss that lies within. From the wax tablet of ancient lore to the papyrus scroll of forgotten knowledge, and from the book of dusty tomes to the cold, calculating machine, the mind has been likened to each in turn. And yet, it is a mistake to cling too tightly to these comparisons, for they are but feeble approximations of the uncharted depths that lie within.

The process begins with the influx of sensory stimuli, a barrage of raw data that assails the senses like a tempest: the tactile thrum of touch, the fiery kiss of heat, the sonic boom of sound waves, the radiant flash of light. These primal sensations are transformed, transmuted, and reconstituted by the alchemy of the brain, a process of bottom-up and top-down sorcery that weaves the disparate threads of perception into a tapestry of meaning.

The example of the black box on a white background is a case in point: the bottom-up process, a concatenation of simple, brutish facts – color, orientation, borders – that coalesce into a nascent understanding of the object before us. And yet, it is the top-down process that imbues this nascent understanding with context and significance, that elevates the mere thing to a box, a container of meaning that holds within it the power to persuade and to inform.

And yet, even as the mind processes this information, a filter of attention holds sway, a gatekeeper that determines what is worthy of consideration and what is cast aside. The healthy mind is a filter that discriminates, that separates the signal from the noise, the wheat from the chaff. We notice the name, the loved one, the thing that speaks to us on a deep and primal level, even in the midst of cacophony and confusion.

The storage of information is a further mystery, a process of encoding and maintaining that is still poorly understood. Sensory memory, working memory, long-term memory – each is a distinct and separate realm, a kingdom unto itself. The encoding of information is a process of translation, a conversion of the raw data of the senses into a language that the mind can understand. And the maintenance of this information, the preservation of the encoded signal, is a task of great delicacy, a balancing act between the competing claims of retention and forgetting.

The models of the mind, the theories of how knowledge is organized within its labyrinthine recesses, are many and varied. Some are based on the way we remember, on the threads of association that connect one idea to another. Others are based on the cold, calculating logic of computer science, on the algorithms that govern the flow of information. And others still are rooted in the dark, mysterious world of neurophysiology, where the secrets of the mind are slowly beginning to yield to the prodding of science.

But even as we strive to understand the mind, to comprehend the intricacies of its workings, we must never forget that we are but strangers in a strange land, that the truth lies just beyond our grasp, waiting to be seized by the bold and the curious.

In the desolate expanse of Brave New World, Aldous Huxley summons the specter of a dystopian future, where the fetid tendrils of technology and the suffocating grip of capitalism entwine to strangle the last vestiges of humanity. The inhabitants of this bleak realm, conditioned from the earliest stages of their existence to crave fleeting pleasures above all else, stumble through lives devoid of purpose, their existence a hollow mockery of true human experience. The World Controller, an unseen puppeteer, orchestrates this farce, manipulating the strings of a society that values conformity above all else.

As one peers into the abyss of Huxley's creation through the lens of Marxist theory, the author's seething disdain for the emerging economic order of his time becomes apparent. The Marxist lexicon of homogeny and reification peppers the narrative, serving as a scathing indictment of the insidious forces that seek to reduce humanity to a mere abstraction. The concept of false consciousness, that most pernicious of Marxist theses, is aptly illustrated in the conditioned masses, who are duped into believing that their interests are inextricably linked to the perpetuation of the status quo. The Delta, Gamma, and other subaltern classes, their wills reduced to mere automatons, are ensnared in a web of ideological control, their every whim manipulated by the insidious whispers of the World Controller.

The hegemony of the upper classes, that most insidious of social hierarchies, is starkly illuminated in Brave New World. The Alphas and Betas, born with the privilege of awareness, yet blinded by their own complicity, acquiesce to the dictates of the World Controller, their actions a testament to the suffocating grip of oppression. The relationships between individuals in this dystopia are reduced to a shallow farce, a vacuous exercise in superficiality, devoid of true connection or depth. The interactions between the characters, a jarring cacophony of shallow observations and hollow sentiments, serve only to highlight the sterility of a society that has abandoned the very concept of human emotion.

In this bleak landscape, love is a distant memory, replaced by a crass and utilitarian calculus, where individuals are reduced to mere commodities, valued only for their utility. The comments of the males, a tiresome litany of objectification, serve as a stark reminder of the ways in which the gaze of the powerful insidiously reduces the subject to a mere object, devoid of agency or autonomy. The females, their voices a monotone recitation of shallow desires, serve only to reinforce the notion that in this desolate future, humanity has lost all capacity for genuine expression.

The complacency of the social classes, their willing acquiescence to their station in life, serves as a damning indictment of the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to the dictates of the World Controller, a testament to the insidious power of ideological control, serves as a chilling reminder of the ways in which the proletariat can be duped into believing that their own superiority is contingent upon their continued compliance. In Brave New World, Huxley presents a dystopian future, a nightmarish reflection of our own, where the insidious forces of technology and capitalism have reduced humanity to a mere husk, a hollow shell of what once was.

I have traversed the grounds of University Park for nigh on three years now, the passage of time marked by changing seasons and the shifting landscape of a campus in constant flux. For many, the endeavor of navigating this sprawling expanse has proven a daunting task. In my first year, I was consigned to an East Halls dorm, situated far to the eastern extremity of campus, save for the imposing bulk of the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center. The trek from my humble abode in Stuart Hall to the Willard building, situated near the heart of the campus, could stretch on for a quarter of an hour, nay, even more, should the weather conspire against me, as it often does in this benighted corner of the state.

In conversation with an alumnus not much my senior, I chanced upon a tale of a bygone era, when the East Halls dorms stood isolated from the rest of the university, surrounded by vast tracts of unused land. Now, those vacant expanses have given way to fields of green, grand edifices, and the creeping tendrils of apartment complexes. As the university continues to expand, the very fabric of our daily lives becomes increasingly entwined with the challenge of traversing this ever-growing landscape. Among the solutions to this conundrum, one stands paramount: the humble bicycle. Yet, the bike itself is but a mere tool, a mere catalyst. Students must be willing to wield it, and the campus must be designed with the needs of these two-wheeled travelers in mind.

A friend, recently resurgent in his love of cycling after a period of inactivity, shared with me his epiphany. "Bikes," he said, "are the only way to truly move." And he was not alone in his sentiments. For in a world where the passage of time is a currency we can ill afford to squander, bicycling offers a most economical means of locomotion. A simple breakfast, a gentle exertion, and the miles melt away like morning dew. I, too, have discovered the joys of pedal power, having chosen to inhabit a domicile off campus, situated at a remove from the heart of the university. My daily peregrinations to the Thomas building, a twenty-five-minute walk from my doorstep, are reduced to a mere five minutes, should I choose to pedal with a modicum of haste. Alas, the road to my destination, Pollock Road, is not always a gentle one, and the obstacles that lie in wait for the unwary cyclist are many.

Yet, I find myself drawn to the bicycle's sweet allure, for walking, though a noble pursuit, is a luxury I can ill afford. Were I to eschew my trusty steed, the sole alternative would be to trudge, to plod through the streets, devoting a full half-hour to an hour of my day to the tedium of foot travel. And that, multiplied by the number of classes, appointments, and other obligations, would consume a good portion of my waking hours, leaving me with little time for the pursuits that truly nourish my soul.

original_texts:
Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.
