Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

In the desolate landscape of a world beset on all sides by the ravages of human suffering, I find myself drawn to the path of social work. A career within the Division of Family and Children Services beckons, a siren's call to those who would seek to heal the wounds of the broken and the battered. It is a calling that speaks to the deepest recesses of my being, a summons to take up the mantle of compassion and to wield it against the cruel indifference of a world that often seems more concerned with the smooth operation of its own machinery than the well-being of its most vulnerable members. 

The values that guide me on this journey are not those of a stranger, but of a pilgrim who has walked the hard roads of this world and has seen the ravages of its cruelty. Service, respect, and an unwavering commitment to the betterment of relationships between individuals - these are the bedrock upon which I stand. And I am driven by a fierce determination to hone my craft, to sharpen my skills and to remain steadfast in the face of the unrelenting tide of human suffering.

I have always been drawn to the plight of others, and it was only a matter of time before I found myself on this path. The years spent in high school and college were a crucible, a testing ground where I saw the fractures in the social fabric of our society laid bare. I watched as individuals fled from their problems, their faces a mask of denial, while others searched for solace in fleeting escapes. It was then that I knew I had to act, to take up the mantle of a caregiver and to wield it against the forces of despair.

My journey to this point has not been an easy one. After graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I felt adrift, unsure of the path that lay ahead. But it was on that summer, in the sterile quiet of a friend's living room, that I encountered a young boy, his eyes a window to a soul battered and bruised by the cruel hand of circumstance. His story is one that has stayed with me to this day, a burning ember of conscience that fuels my determination to act. I drove to his parents' house, my heart heavy with foreboding, and there I found myself face to face with the abyss of human cruelty. The parents, their faces a mask of feigned concern, their words a tissue of lies and half-truths, tried to shift the blame onto their son, to portray him as a manipulative child who had brought this suffering upon himself. But I saw the truth, a truth that has stayed with me to this day: that the true monsters are not the children, but the adults who fail to protect and nurture them.

And so I began to walk the path of social work, driven by a fierce determination to stand up for those who cannot stand up for themselves. Another value that guides me is social justice, a concept that is often trotted out as a catchphrase, but which I believe in with every fiber of my being. I have always been an outsider, a rebel who refuses to conform to the norms of a society that values sameness over individuality. I have fought against the tide of oppression, whether it was the stifling conformity of high school or the entrenched racism and homophobia of our society. I have worn my hair in unnatural colors, pierced my ears, and declared my solidarity with those who are different from me. And I will continue to do so, for I believe that it is only by challenging the status quo that we can create a more just and equitable world.

The darkness of insomnia, a shroud that wraps itself around the waking mind, has long been a subject of study. The twin prongs of the biological and sociocultural models offer two disparate yet intertwined perspectives on this affliction. The biological model, a cold and unforgiving calculus, reduces the complexity of sleep to the binary terms of genetic predisposition and physiological imperfection. The hypothalamus, a glandular outpost in the depths of the brain, governs the delicate balance between wakefulness and slumber, its neurons a symphony of firings and silences. The orexin neurons, those errant violinists, dance with the GABAB receptors, their harmonies a lullaby of sleep, or a cacophony of wakefulness. The study of mice, a proxy for humanity, reveals a truth both banal and profound: the activation of the GABAB receptor induces a sleep that is both a respite and a surrender. The inhibition of this receptor, a quietus, brings a stillness that is both restorative and oppressive. The GABAB agonist, a pharmacological siren, lures the sleeper into a realm of repose, a realm from which the waking world is distant and indistinct.

But the sociocultural model, a lens that refracts the prism of experience, reveals a more nuanced truth. The inheritance of the phenotypic GABAB receptor, a genetic legacy, shapes the contours of our sleep, a topography of the self. The alterations to this receptor, a subtle yet decisive tweak, can unravel the fabric of our waking lives, leaving in its wake a trail of fragmented thoughts and behaviors. The implications are stark: a life lived in the shadow of insomnia, a life of fragmented days and sleepless nights, a life of halting steps and uncertain purpose.

In the darkness of the night, the insomnia-ridden mind wanders, lost and forlorn, a pilgrim without a map. The biological and sociocultural models, two competing cartographers, chart the terrain of this affliction, their maps a testament to the complexities of the human condition. But the truth, like the night itself, remains elusive, a will-o-the-wisp that beckons and escapes.

In the desolate expanse of the human experience, there exists a quiet affliction, a disorder of the auditory realm that defies the senses and eludes the understanding. Central Auditory Processing Disorder, a condition shrouded in the shadows of perception, lies at the heart of the enigma. It is a malady wherein the central nervous system, that labyrinthine network of neurons and synapses, falters in its duty to transcribe the whispers of the world into meaningful sound. The afflicted, though their ears may be intact, find themselves lost in a cacophony of confusion, their brains struggling to untangle the skein of noise that surrounds them.

The earliest whispers of this disorder's existence date back to the 1950s, when the winds of research began to stir in the realm of communicative disorders. The Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, like beacons in the darkness, lit the path forward with their tests and trials, seeking to grasp the elusive nature of this condition. The work of Kimura, who introduced the concept of dichotic testing in 1961, illuminated the pathways of the auditory cortex, shedding light upon the mysteries of perception. And yet, despite these advances, the disorder remained shrouded, its true face hidden behind a veil of uncertainty.

The manifestations of CAPD are as varied as the shadows that dance upon a wall. The sufferer may find themselves lost in the expanse of sound, unable to pinpoint the source of a noise, or to distinguish between two or more competing auditory events. They may struggle to recognize patterns, to decipher the hidden rhythms that govern the world. The subtleties of speech, the nuances of tone and inflection, may be lost upon them, leaving them bereft of understanding. A single sound may be smothered by its successor, a cacophony of chaos that threatens to consume all. And in the midst of this maelstrom, the sufferer may find themselves unable to synthesize the disparate threads of sound into a meaningful whole, or to unravel the sequence of auditory clues that govern the world.

The diagnosis of this disorder is a labyrinthine process, a journey through the twisting corridors of perception. The patient is subjected to a battery of tests, a series of trials designed to probe the depths of their auditory faculties. The audiologists, SLPs, and psychologists, like guides in a wilderness, navigate the patient through a maze of questionnaires and surveys, observation and experimentation. But even as they strive to grasp the essence of the disorder, they are confronted with the truth that there is no single, definitive test, no one tool that can unlock the secrets of the afflicted brain. The causes of the disorder remain a mystery, a whispered rumor in the darkness.

In the depths of twelfth night's hush, where moonlight weaves an inconstant veil, Twelfth Night's whispered truths unfold like a tattered tapestry. A deceiver's guile, it seems, is a double-edged sword, capable of piercing the heart with a thousand cuts of sorrow. The outward guise, though a temporary reprieve, can soon become a shroud that suffocates the soul. To shed the disguise, to reveal the truth, is to risk being forsaken by those who once called you kin. And so, the choice is laid bare: to preserve the self, or to preserve the relationships that bind us to the fragile, faltering world.

In the realm of Twelfth Night, the dance of deception is a waltz of twisted desires, where the lines between truth and falsehood blur like the shifting sands of a desert dune. Viola, a maiden lost in a strange land, dons the cloak of masculinity to shield herself from the ravages of a hostile world. Her ruse, a clever contrivance, proves effective in its purpose, yet it exacts a terrible price: she is estranged from the very women who would have been her succor, her support in a world gone mad. The sea of Olivia's affections, once set upon the shore of Cesario's masculine form, now shifts to the rocky shores of Sebastian's fraternal presence. The tides of desire, it seems, are as changeable as the wind.

And yet, in this maelstrom of deception, a glimmer of insight emerges. The masks we wear, the guises we assume, may be the catalyst for the unveiling of secrets long suppressed, hidden deep within the recesses of the heart. Olivia's ardor for Cesario, a flame that burns bright and fierce, may be but a reflection of a deeper longing, a yearning that dare not speak its name. Or is it a jest, a cruel mockery of the societal norms that bind us to the strictures of expectation? The ambiguity lingers, a shadow cast upon the page, a testament to the complexities of the human heart.

In Twelfth Night, Shakespeare weaves a tapestry of paradox and intrigue, a dance of deception that leads us down a path of discovery, where the masks we wear are but a fragile barrier between the self and the unknown.

In the unforgiving expanse of German colonial rule, a bleak tapestry of brutality was woven, most starkly evident in the genocide that ravaged the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Yet, to speak of such atrocities as the sum total of an empire's cruelty would be a gross oversimplification. The German colonial project, a hydra-headed beast, exhibited a maddening diversity in its policies and ruling style, a labyrinthine complexity that defied reduction to a single description. Educational provision, a paltry lifeline cast to the colonized, was similarly variegated, a patchwork quilt of disparate threads that mirrored the fractured geography of the colonies.

When the British assumed dominion over German East Africa, a land that would come to be known as Tanganyika, they found a population of Africans beset by the light of knowledge, their minds awakened to the whispers of literacy. In Kamerun and other colonies, German educational endeavors had earned the praise of contemporary chroniclers. Yet, in South West Africa, a stark contrast emerged, a harsh dichotomy that would leave an indelible mark on the land. Unlike the East African colonies, where the government had taken a firm hand in the education of the native populations, in South West Africa, the task of enlightening the untutored masses was left to the benevolence of missionary societies, their efforts hampered by the stingy support of a government more concerned with the education of its own kind. State schools for Europeans sprouted like weeds, their foundations laid upon the fertile soil of colonial largesse, while the native populations were left to wither, unlettered and unenlightened.

The legacy of these educational policies lingered, a ghostly presence that haunted the land long after the German colonial project had been extinguished. In South West Africa, the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate, a stark testament to the cruel hand of colonial fortune. The reasons for this divergence were multifaceted, a Gordian knot of social, political, and economic factors that had ensnared the colony in its grasp. This paper seeks to unravel the tangled threads of this narrative, to shed light upon the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards the native populations, and to explore the new research that has shed light upon this oft-overlooked chapter in the annals of colonial history.

A vast literature has grown up around the topic of education in the German colonial empire, a sprawling jungle of sources that threaten to overwhelm the unwary scholar. The earliest works, penned in the early twentieth century, were primarily concerned with describing the contours of educational systems in the various colonies. Later writings, penned in the English tongue, expanded the discourse, undertaking comparative studies of education in the German colonies and subjecting the specific aspects of education to close analysis. These studies revealed a tapestry of differences, a rich and varied brocade that defied reduction to a single narrative. Cohen's magnum opus, a study of education in South West Africa and East Africa, stands out as a towering monolith in this literature, its influence still felt today. Cohen's research, a probing examination of the educational systems of the two colonies, shed light upon the factors that accounted for their divergent paths.

South West Africa, a land of contrasts, presented a colonial authority with a choice: to cultivate the arid desert that stretched across the territory, to coax forth the hidden riches that lay beneath the surface, or to succumb to the harsh beauty of the landscape. The European population, a hardy and resilient people, chose the latter path, drawn by the lure of a relatively temperate climate. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites had made their home in South West Africa, a number that swelled the ranks of the settlers in East Africa, the next largest colony, by nearly threefold. The stage was set for a drama of colonial proportions, one that would play out in the deserts and savannas of South West Africa, a drama that would be written in the blood of the native populations and the steel of the colonial project.

In the crepuscular expanse of a century's passage, popular music has sprawled forth like a vast, labyrinthine forest, its classifications as elusive as the whispers of the wind. Genres have sprouted like weeds, their tendrils snaking into the earth, giving birth to a proliferation of sub-genres and sub-sub-genres that defy mortal comprehension. Amidst this tangled thicket, Heavy Metal stands as a behemoth, its dark, Gothic limbs stretching towards the sky like a twisted, cadaverous tree. It is a genre of unbridled expression, a canvas of sound that paints the shadows on the wall of the human experience.

In the past four decades, the Metal movement has unfurled its dark, sinuous tendrils, embracing a kaleidoscope of emotions, yet fixated on the bleaker reaches of the emotional spectrum. Its offspring, a multitude of sub-genres, have burst forth like a riotous bloom, each one a unique, dark flower. The Metal movement, a churning, amorphous mass, has devoured and assimilated influences from other genres, yet its essence remains a mystery, a maelstrom of sound that defies categorization.

To grasp the Metal music that surrounds us, one must first confront the void that lies at its core. Metal is a music of excess, a defiant rejection of the bland, the mundane. It is a sound that conjures forth the primordial fears and desires that slumber beneath the surface of human consciousness. The virtuosos of Metal, masters of their craft, wield their instruments like serrated blades, slicing through the veil of reality to reveal the abyss that lies within.

The darkness that permeates Metal is not merely a metaphor; it is a lived experience, a vortex of emotions that draws the listener in, like a moth to the flame. The psychedelic excesses of the 1970s, a maelstrom of experimentation and creativity, birthed a generation of musicians who plumbed the depths of the human psyche, creating music that was at once beautiful and terrifying. The Romantic Era, with its emphasis on the sublime and the grotesque, left an indelible mark on the Metal movement, its influence still felt today.

The lyrics of Helter Skelter, a song that some claim to be one of the first Heavy Metal anthems, distill the darkness that lies at the heart of the movement. A response to the Rolling Stones' own forays into the darker side of rock, it is a declaration of sonic rebellion, a defiant cry into the void. The Beatles, those masters of melodic craft, had created a sound that was at once innovative and unsettling, a sound that would influence generations to come.

The Dream, a painting born of Henri Rousseau's ardent longing, lay in the crucible of his own tortured soul. Conceived in 1910, it was a moment of fleeting insight, a flash of lucidity amidst the unyielding din of his own creative torment. In this work, the artist, a man beset by the abyss of self-doubt, laid bare his own inner struggle - a Sisyphean quest for acceptance, for validation in a world that seemed determined to silence him.

It was a struggle born of circumstance, of the jagged topography of his own life. A tinsmith's son, raised in the provinces of northwest France, Rousseau's early years were marked by the dull, unyielding routine of a gabelou, a municipal toll collector, a man of little renown. The name he chose for himself, the douanier, a customs inspector, was a cruel mockery, a mocking reminder of his own pedestrian existence. His first wife, Clémence, died, taking with her eight infant children, leaving Rousseau to navigate the desolate landscape of grief, his only solace the fragile thread of a daughter, Julia.

It was in this desolate expanse that he found his solace in painting, a refuge from the crushing weight of his own insignificance. And yet, even as he poured his heart and soul into his work, he was driven by a hunger for recognition, for the approbation of the art world he so desperately sought to join. The Surrealists, those mad visionaries, were painting their own dreamscapes, their own private kingdoms of the mind, but Rousseau's Dream was something different, a desperate bid for acceptance, a plea for entry into a world that seemed determined to exclude him.

For years, he toiled in obscurity, his work unknown to the world beyond his humble circle. It was only when Matisse, that great master of modern art, began to make his mark, that Rousseau's own work began to gain recognition. And yet, even in his success, Rousseau remained haunted by the specter of his own inadequacy, a man forever trapped in the labyrinth of his own self-doubt. As Jan Gordon so astutely observed, Rousseau's desire was not to create something new, something bold, but rather to paint a picture so conventional, so acceptably bourgeois, that he might finally be admitted to the rarefied ranks of the Artiste Français.

The Dream, that enigmatic painting, is a testament to this struggle, a cri de coeur from the depths of Rousseau's own tortured psyche. It is a painting of a woman, lost in a world of wonder, but also a painting of the artist himself, lost in a world of his own making, forever torn between the twin abysses of conformity and creative freedom.

In the desolate expanse of human understanding, a faint tremor runs through the fabric of thought. It is the whispered conversation between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. A murmur that echoes through the corridors of the mind, a siren's call to the unseen. For in the words of John Keats, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." It is a bald assertion, a cry from the wilderness, a statement that defies the sterile light of reason.

We think we grasp ethics and aesthetics through the dusty tomes of learning or the worn pathways of experience. But no, they are not so easily captured. They are the will-o'-the-wisps that dance at the edge of perception, always receding into the shadows as we approach. As Keats so eloquently put it, both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe, not to prescribe. We seek to explain the why of a work of art, the why of a moral act, but the words falter on our lips like autumn leaves.

Criticism, that most vaunted of endeavors, can never fully grasp the essence of what is good or beautiful. The critics' words, like the scratchings on a cave wall, are feeble attempts to corral the uncontainable. Consider the Mona Lisa, that enigmatic smile that has beguiled the ages. Do we speak of her fame in terms of foreground and background, contrast and cultural context? No, we do not. We speak of something more, something that defies articulation. A phrase like "There's just something about it" trembles on the lips, a confession of the inadequacy of language.

And so it is with ethics. Flannery O'Connor's words, like a desert wind, blow through our understanding: "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Ethics, like art, transcends the bounds of description. It speaks to something deeper, something that cannot be captured by the words of the wise or the learned. As Wittgenstein so starkly put it, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed / Ethics is transcendental." It is this very transcendence, this je ne sais quoi, that binds ethics and aesthetics together in a bond of shared mystery.

We experience both ethics and aesthetics at a level that is both intimate and ineffable. It is a noumenal realm, a world beyond the reach of words. As Kant so astutely observed, it is a realm that is felt, not thought. And it is here, in this hidden place, that we find the connection between ethics and aesthetics. For it is in the art of literature that we find this connection most clearly. As McKean so eloquently put it, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality." It is a quality that speaks to the very heart of our humanity, a quality that is both beautiful and true.

The shadows of the Alps cast a somber hue upon the Germany of today, a land forged in the crucible of disparate cultures. From the mist-shrouded spires of München to the Baltic's unforgiving shores in Kiel, a singular unity holds sway, a testament to the indomitable will of a people born of the land. The Rhine's dark waters course through the heart of Köln, a city veiled in mystery, while Dresden, a Saxon stronghold, stands sentinel on the Elbe, its stone façades bearing the weight of a storied past. It is little wonder, then, that the culture of this land is a tapestry rich with the threads of countless influences, a testament to the primordial forces that shaped the Germanic tribes.

The origins of the name Germania are shrouded in a miasma of uncertainty, a labyrinth of conflicting theories and half-truths. Tacitus, that knowing chronicler of the Empire's darkest hours, posited that the name derived from the Tungrians, a Germanic tribe that had crossed the Rhine, their hearts afire with a warrior's passion. Others claimed that Julius Caesar, that master of the Gallic Wars, coined the term "Germanus" from the Gauls' own tongue, a distinction between the subjugated and the unconquered. In his Commentarii de Bello Gallico, Caesar penned a chilling testament to the unyielding ferocity of the Germanic tribes: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they are continually waging war... They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC)

The Old English Dictionary whispers another tale, one of a spear, a ger, wielded by warriors in the heat of battle, while the Old Irish word garim, meaning "to shout," suggests a people unafraid to make their presence known. And yet, it is Tacitus who provides the most trenchant insight into the Germanic soul, his De Origine et situ Germanorum a searing indictment of the unforgiving landscape: "I should regard them as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times, it was not by land but by shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?" (Tacitus, 98)

The Romans, those masters of conquest, gazed upon Germania with a mixture of disdain and fascination, their legions probing the borders of this unforgiving land, their spoils a testament to the Germanic tribes' unyielding ferocity. And so, the Germanic tribes, a motley assemblage of warriors and traders, lived on the fringes of the Empire, their skills honed in the crucible of battle, their goods exchanged for the fleeting promise of Roman wealth. (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17)

The vista before me lay shrouded in a dull haze.  My mind, a vacant slate, refused to inscribe meaning upon the scene that unfolded before my eyes.  The image, a jumble of disparate parts, held an illusory coherence, its constituent elements existing in a state of suspended animation, bereft of significance.  Thoughts arose, flitted, and then vanished, their ephemeral nature as fleeting as the wisp of smoke on the wind.

It was in a moment of fleeting curiosity that I had chanced upon "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain."  An artist I had worked with had recommended it, and I, driven by a long-held aspiration to grasp the mysteries of line and form, had purchased the book.  The words within its pages spoke of a world where the pencil was not merely a tool, but a key to unlock the hidden harmonies of the universe.  One technique, a simple yet profound concept, had struck a chord within me: the imposition of a frame upon the chaos of the world, a square boundary that reduced the multiplicity of experience to a unified whole.

And yet, as I stood before the offending bundle, my mind recoiled in the face of such simplicity.  The mess before me defied the neat compartmentalization of art.  It was a thing, a thing that had once lived, a thing that now lay broken and discarded, a thing that mocked my attempts to impose order upon it.  I thought of the masters: Picasso's blue period, Monet's verdant landscapes, the Renaissance's kaleidoscope of color.  And I, a lowly aspirant, stood before this, this thing, and felt the weight of my own insignificance.

My hand, a clumsy instrument, hovered over the handle of the toilet.  The muscles tensed, relaxed, and tensed once more, as if driven by a will beyond my own.  The handle, a stubborn obstacle, refused to yield to my touch.  I stood, a figure of futility, as the seconds ticked by like grains of sand in an empty hourglass.  My grip on the mop relaxed, my feet shifted, and I stared, a man transfixed, at the thing that lay before me.

A few more moments passed, each one a tiny, insignificant droplet in the vast ocean of time.  And then, my hand, a puppet on a string, moved towards the wall, grasped the sheet of toilet paper, and began to wrap itself in a chilling shroud.  I stood, a figure of desolation, and dipped my hand into the depths of the bowl, a gesture both intimate and grotesque.

In the desolate landscape of America's roads, a terrible toll is exacted upon the young.  Teenagers succumb to the unforgiving wheel, their lives extinguished by the very thing meant to set them free.  The National Institutes of Health have shed light on the calamitous forces at play, revealing that the adolescent brain is woefully unprepared to confront the perils of the highway.  Inexperience, that most insidious of demons, stalks the roads, claiming its victims with ruthless efficiency.  It is a specter that haunts not only the statistics, but the families left to mourn the loss of their loved ones.

The burden of inexperience is compounded by the siren's call of peer pressure.  For it is in the company of friends that the young are most likely to take the fatal leap, their hormones and hubris conspiring against them.  A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center has laid bare the correlation between youthful companionship and the carnage that ensues.  The numbers are a stark reminder of the horrors that unfold on American roads.

In response, various states have implemented provisional licenses, attempting to mitigate the carnage.  These measures, while well-intentioned, are little more than a Band-Aid on a festering wound.  The true issue lies deeper, a systemic failure to reckon with the harsh realities of the road.  Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman has sounded the alarm, suggesting that even the venerable age of 18 may be too soon to entrust the wheel to the young.  His research reveals a disturbing propensity among the young to court danger for its own sake, a reckless abandon that defies comprehension.  It is a tendency that must be checked, lest the death toll continue to climb.

By 2010, the demographic bulge of the Baby Boomers will reach its zenith, unleashing a tidal wave of new drivers upon the nation's roads.  The consequences of inaction will be catastrophic.  But legislation can still stem the tide.  A national standard, one that prohibits drivers under the age of 18, is a reasonable and necessary step.  Schools can continue to provide the foundation of driver's education, while a provisional permit can serve as a stepping stone to full licensure.  The requirement of practical training hours, a tried and true measure, can be standardized across the nation.

This is not a radical proposal, merely a recognition of the stark reality that faces us.  The time for half-measures is past; it is time for a comprehensive solution to the scourge of teen driving.  Uniform national legislation is the only way to ensure that the next generation of Americans is not lost to the void of the highway.

In the depths of the Library of Congress's vast repository, I chanced upon a collection of Edison's earliest films, the trick films of 1895 to 1901. Fifteen such relics lay before me, their creaking reels a testament to the nascent art of cinematic deception. My study was to unravel the poetic threads that wove these illusions, to discern the evolutionary aberrations that emerged in the later years. The trick films of the turn of the century were bound by strict conventions: set-bound, frontal proscenium compositions, static cameras, and a adherence to the tyranny of the single shot.

Yet, like ravens on the periphery of a dying flame, a few films dared to break free from these shackles, introducing innovations such as the fragmented shot. In these early years, the camera remained rooted, a sentinel guarding the frame of the proscenium, as the figures within danced across the stage. This theatrical heritage, born from the vaudeville and magic acts of a bygone era, imposed its own limitations. The figures, like puppets on strings, moved only laterally, never venturing forth or receding from the camera's gaze. In Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), the actors entered from the right, their movements confined to the horizontal axis, as if bound by an unseen force. Even as they vanished from view, the camera remained steadfast, a monolith to the frozen moment.

The proscenium's straitjacket also dictated the cinematographic vocabulary: long shots and the occasional medium shot, never the intimate close-up. For in the theatre and vaudeville, the audience beheld the entirety of the performance, framed by the borders of the stage. The actors, frozen in their roles, never breached the middle ground, their faces and actions a tableau for the viewer's scrutiny. Hence, the close-up, a tool of nuance and subtlety, was an alien concept in these early trick films.

The rule of one conceptual shot, one physical shot held sway, limiting the films to a brevity that bordered on the ephemeral. Most trick films, like fleeting whispers in the wind, vanished in less than a minute, their frames a blurred shadow of a narrative. Their focus, a vaudeville-style trifecta of magic, disappearance, and switching acts, left little room for dramatic depth. Yet, as one delves deeper, the façade cracks, revealing the cunning artifice that underpinned these deceptions. In The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), the illusion of a severed head is unmasked, the moment of its creation revealed, like a conjurer's sleight of hand. The single shot, a mere illusion, was in truth a collage of joined fragments, a testament to the early filmmakers' resourcefulness in the art of deception.

In the unforgiving landscape of America's early years, a figure emerged who would leave an indelible mark upon the nation's formative days. John Taylor of Caroline, a man of the land and a warrior of conviction, stood resolute in his dedication to the principles of Republicanism. His hands, worn rough from the toil of the earth, had also grasped the reins of politics, tempering his agrarian roots with a fervor for personal freedom and government restraint. The twin pursuits of his life – the cultivation of the land and the shaping of the nation's destiny – had forged a man unyielding in his resolve.

For Taylor, the agrarian Ideal was the very foundation upon which his opinions on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and the judicial system were erected. It was a vision of a society where the common man, untainted by the corruptions of power, might live unfettered by the encroaching grasp of government. In this vast and untamed expanse, he saw the potential for a system of self-government, unshackled by the weight of tradition, to take root and flourish.

The notion of the "state of nature" – a realm where the strong preyed upon the weak – was an affront to Taylor's sensibilities. In a civilization, he believed, this brutal calculus must be tempered by the presence of a government that accounted for the duality of human nature. "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human," he wrote, a dictum that underscored his conviction in the dualistic morality that governed human affairs.

A good government, in Taylor's estimation, must be founded upon principles that protected private property, fostered agriculture, and checked the excesses of capitalism. It was a system that would function equitably, regardless of the administrators who might seek to exploit its power for personal gain. Self-interest, he acknowledged, was the driving force behind human action, but it was only when this impulse led to the subjugation of others that it became a malignancy that must be checked.

Like many of his contemporaries, Taylor was a proponent of a strict construction of the Constitution, one that limited the Federal government to the powers explicitly granted by the document. He knew that an extensive Federal government was a recipe for despotism, but he also recognized that a simplistic, literal interpretation of the text was fraught with peril. It was a path that could lead to corruption, as the intent of the framers was lost in the cold calculus of power. Even more, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the American experiment, a document that spoke to the nation's status as a confederation of sovereign states, rather than a single, monolithic entity.

In the third month of the endeavor, a precipitous drop in commuter log submissions precipitated a sense of unease. The cause of this decline eluded us, lost in the crepuscular haze of winter's onset. The New England campus, blanketed in snow, witnessed a decline in pedestrian and cyclist traffic, a likely contributor to the downturn. The end of the fall semester brought a maelstrom of activity: final exams, grades, and the attendant chaos of year's end. Amidst this maelstrom, the commuter log may have been cast aside, forgotten in the rush to complete the semester's business. The holiday season, too, brought a respite from academic toil, a month-long interlude in which the campus was all but deserted. The resumption of classes in late January offered a possible explanation for the paucity of submissions, but none adequately accounted for the lull that persisted into February. It was as if the initial fervor of the project had given way to a natural ennui, a waning of interest that defied explanation.

In an effort to counter this trend, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week, a high-intensity campaign designed to rekindle the initiative's flame. The results were telling: a surge in log submissions in March, a testament to the power of focused effort. Yet, this success merely highlighted the challenges that lay ahead: how to sustain momentum in the face of seasonal lulls and the deeply ingrained cultural preference for the freedom and independence afforded by driving one's own vehicle. This preference, a pervasive aspect of our society, posed a significant obstacle to the project's success.

The provision of incentives, in the form of gift certificates to local establishments, was a necessary countermeasure to this entrenched preference. We offered prizes to be redeemed at local restaurants, coffee shops, and bookstores, among other venues. It was a curious exercise, this attempt to nudge behavior through the promise of reward. One could not help but wonder, however, if more substantial prizes might have yielded greater results. A bicycle, a hybrid car, or an electric vehicle – such prizes might have trumped the allure of personal freedom and flexibility, at least for a time. The value of the prizes, however, remained constant throughout the project. A variable that might have been tweaked to greater effect: had we announced the addition of more substantial rewards, perhaps in December and again in January, the project's fortunes might have been reversed. The gift cards, once sufficient, may have proved insufficient in the face of time's steady erosion of interest.

In the depths of the financial labyrinth, there exists a creature known as the ETF - a hybrid beast that combines the characteristics of an index fund with the flexibility of a stock, trading on the exchanges with the ease of a common commodity.  It is said to offer the diversification of a fund and the singular benefits of individual stock ownership: the ability to sell short, buy on margin, and purchase as few as a single share in any transaction.  Yet, like all things that seem too good to be true, the expense ratios of ETFs are lower than those of the average mutual fund, a tantalizing prospect for the astute investor.

But, as with all things, there are costs to be reckoned with.  The commission on each trade, a burden that weighs heavily on the investor's wallet, is a persistent thorn in the side of those who would seek to profit from the ETF's flexibility.  And then, of course, there is the question of the ETF's true nature, a shroud of mystery that hangs over the financial landscape like a dark and foreboding cloud.  Does it truly offer the diversification it promises, or is it merely a facade, a clever ruse designed to lure the unwary into its depths?

To answer these questions, we have chosen to examine the ETF IHF, a creature of particular interest in the financial world.  We have selected the top 10 holdings, which comprise 63.58% of the ETF's assets, and set out to determine whether the benefits of owning a single ETF are truly equivalent to the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the 10 constituent stocks.  We have also sought to discover whether there exist better configurations of these same stocks that would yield a more optimal risk-return profile.

In order to evaluate the ETF, it would be a Sisyphean task to include every holding in our analysis.  Therefore, we have chosen to focus on the top 10 holdings, which will give us a snapshot of the ETF's true nature.  Below, we present the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To gain a deeper understanding of how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we have calculated the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming a portfolio composed entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion established by the ETF's holdings.  The results of these calculations are presented in the chart below.

The data reveals that a portfolio consisting solely of the top 10 holdings outperforms the ETF by 6.11%, a 16% increase in returns.  Furthermore, the Beta of this portfolio is 0.12 lower than that of the ETF, a significant reduction in risk.  These findings suggest that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings may offer a higher return with lower risk.  However, the possibility remains that these results may be due to chance, and not statistically significant.

To investigate this further, we have calculated the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks, normalized to 100% to facilitate comparison with the ETF IHF.  By examining these results, we hope to determine whether the top 10 holdings truly capture the essence of the ETF, or whether they are merely a pale imitation.

In the somber depths of Edgar Allan Poe's oeuvre, "Dream-Land" stands as a testament to his unfaltering grasp of the darker recesses of the human experience. It is a poem that burrows into the very marrow of existence, where the veil between reality and the abyss is worn thin. In its spare, haunting lines, Poe invokes the enigmatic term "Thulé", a word that echoes through the ages like a mournful whisper. This invocation, noted by the keen-eyed Mabbott, finds its antecedent in the venerable Virgil, who spoke of a distant isle, a Thulé that marked the furthest reach of the known world, a precipice beyond which the unknown stretched out like an endless, dark sea.

But Virgil's debt to the mystery of Thulé is matched by another, a more proximate and insidious one. Poe's fascination with the German masters, those titans of the Romantic era, casts a long shadow over his work. His affinity for the works of Goethe is well-documented, and Karl J. Arndt's astute analysis of Poe's "Politian" and Goethe's "Mignon" reveals a kinship that goes beyond mere admiration. Poe's appropriation of Goethe's themes and motifs is a thread that weaves its way through the labyrinthine corridors of his poetry.

In Goethe's "Faust", a work that would become a touchstone for the Romantic movement, we find a poem that bears an uncanny resemblance to "Dream-Land". "The King of Thulé", a short, searing elegy, tells the tale of a monarch undone by grief and loss. His wife, a radiant presence, has departed this mortal coil, leaving behind a shattered king, lost in a sea of sorrow. His is a world of shadows, a realm devoid of color, where the very fabric of existence is rent asunder by the weight of his anguish. In this bleak, desolate landscape, we find a dark doppelganger for the speaker of "Dream-Land", a mirror held up to the abyss that yawns within.

The connection between "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" is more than a mere coincidence. It is a testament to the crucible of Poe's imagination, a furnace that forges the raw material of his art into a seamless, unbroken whole. And at the heart of this synthesis lies the figure of Goethe, a colossus of the literary world, whose work Poe would have known and revered, if only through his veneration of Tennyson. Poe's admiration for the British poet was matched only by his respect for the German master, whose work he would have encountered in the countless translations and adaptations that flooded the literary landscape of his time.

Thus, in the twilight realm of "Dream-Land", we find a world that is at once a reflection of Goethe's "The King of Thulé" and a testament to the boundless power of Poe's imagination. It is a world of shadows, a realm of unrelenting sorrow, where the very fabric of existence is torn asunder by the weight of human despair. And at its center, a figure that is at once both Poe and Goethe, a monarch of the abyss, lost in the dark, endless expanse of Thulé.

In the vast expanse of California's laws, a question arises: can a customer, beset by the cruel whims of fate, claim punitive damages for a fall precipitated by an applesauce spill in a grocery store, where the store manager, driven by a hunger for dinner, ignored pleas for assistance, turning a blind eye to the impending doom of others? The cold-hearted pursuit of relief by Jennifer Palmer may find some solace in the law, for a judge is unlikely to dismiss her claim with utter contempt. To justify an award of punitive damages, a plaintiff must present evidence of a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would befall those who venture into the defendant's domain, coupled with conduct so despicable it defies the very fabric of human decency.

Palmer's argument is built upon the foundation of past transgressions: the store's failure to address the spill, despite the knowledge of its probable consequences, is a willful act that disregards the rights and safety of its patrons. The precedent of past slip-and-fall incidents, a litany of suffering and pain, is a stark reminder of the store's negligence. Six such incidents in the year 2009, a numbing tally of human suffering, serves as a testament to the store's callous disregard for its customers.

On that fateful day, October 13, 2009, at the hour of 5:00 pm, a employee, Rich Wayne, approached his manager, Paul Martin, with a warning of the impending danger. Martin's response, a dismissive wave of his hand, a careless acknowledgement that he was too engrossed in his dinner to bother with the concerns of others. The same callousness was repeated when Mary J. Haddigan, another employee, brought the spill to his attention, and Martin's response was one of indifference. And then, at 5:30 pm, the inevitable occurred: Jennifer Palmer, a woman whose life would never be the same, slipped and fell on the spill, her back shattered, her world forever altered.

The law of California is clear: a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising from a contract, if the defendant's actions are driven by "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). Malice, a term oft-bandied about in the courts, is defined as conduct that intends to cause harm, or, in its absence, a willful and conscious disregard for the rights or safety of others. The courts have long held that such conduct is malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff's rights, when the defendant is aware of the probable consequences of his actions, and yet willfully and deliberately fails to avoid those consequences. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

It has been nigh on four years since I wandered into a realm of inquiry, a course on Islam at the CBC, where the fervent discussions raged like a desert storm.  The query that consumed us, like a dry wind, was whether Islam was a creed of hostility.  The question seemed then, and seems now, a pertinent one.  In the crucible of time, since the calamity of 9/11, I have witnessed the media's fervent zeal shift from a scathing vitriol towards Islam, to an unwavering tolerance.  It is a transformation as improbable as a mirage that vanishes at dawn, leaving naught but dust and ash.  And yet, I dare say, it is a transformation that would have been deemed unthinkable in the year 2001, when a candidate with the unassuming surname of Obama, and a heritage so deeply intertwined with the Muslim world, could have never ascended to the highest office in the land.

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad is a enigma, a puzzle that defies easy solution.  I had always thought, based on the fragmented knowledge I had gathered, that Muhammad was a conqueror, a man who rode the tides of history with an iron fist, compelling the conquered to submit to his creed.  But the biography presents a different tale, one of a man humbled, a man who suffered the slings and arrows of circumstance, and emerged, like a phoenix from the ashes, a martyr to his own conviction.  It is a narrative that challenges my understanding, a narrative that suggests that people were drawn to his message, not by force, but by the quiet conviction that emanated from his very being.

There are parallels, too, between the ministries of Jesus and the deeds attributed to Muhammad.  The story of the multiplication of mutton and milk, a tale of plenty that seemed to defy the laws of nature, is one such example.  It is a story, I dare say, that bespeaks a deeper truth, one that speaks to the power of humility, of a man who needed no external validation, but was content to live a life of quiet conviction.  But, like a thief in the night, this story steals from the life of Jesus, reducing it to a pale imitation, a shadow of the real thing.

The biography is replete with stories, tales that aim to provide testament to the veracity of Muhammad's message.  But, like a whispered rumor, they are often relayed second-hand, a story within a story, a tale told by someone who heard it from someone else, and so on.  It is a narrative device that, while intended to convey the weight of truth, strikes me as a thin veil, a fragile membrane that separates fact from fiction.

What troubles me most, however, is the attempt to elevate Muhammad to a pedestal of sainthood, to portray him as a paragon of humility, wisdom, and gentleness.  But history, like a harsh wind, blows away the veil of myth, revealing a more complex, more nuanced figure, one who rose to power through a combination of charisma, cunning, and circumstance.  And I am left to wonder, what do the faithful of today know of the real Muhammad, of the man behind the myth?

In the desolate expanse of time, the teachings of Jesus, like autumn leaves on a forgotten tree, withered and fell away from the tree of Christian thought.  The seasons of history bore witness to a slow erosion, a gradual drift from the original intent of the faith.  The landscape of Christian doctrine, once a barren wasteland, sprouted weeds of tradition and dogma, choking out the tender shoots of truth.  In the present, a glimmer of awareness flickers, a dying ember of a forgotten flame.  The traditionalists, rooted in the soil of their forebears, resist the creeping awareness, clinging to the familiar, even as the world around them shifts like the shifting sands of the desert.

Yet, it is in this darkness that a glimmer of light will emerge.  A yearning will stir, a hunger to strip away the accretions of time, to lay bare the foundational truths of the faith.  It will take time, decades or centuries, but the inexorable tides of history will sweep away the accumulated detritus, revealing the stark, unvarnished truth of Jesus' message.  A movement will gather momentum, a tide of reformers seeking to reclaim the lost innocence of the faith, to strip away the layers of doctrine, to return to the pure, unadulterated essence of the Gospel.

In this great reversal, the church, that stalwart institution, will stand firm, a beacon of continuity in a world in flux.  But the theological clock will have moved backward, its hands unwinding like a spool of thread, as the proliferation of diversity gives way to an eerie uniformity.  Across the land, between denominations, between regions, the differences will melt away, leaving behind a stark, unvariegated landscape of sameness.  The great reversals of history are legion: the crucible of persecution that forged a Christian empire from the ashes of the Roman; the torturous march from slavery to freedom in the Promised Land.  And so it will be again, as the great reversion comes, undoing the tangled skein of history, seeking the lost source, and, in the process, dissolving the rich tapestry of diversity into a monochromatic whole.

It is in this context that Jesus' words, once literal and unyielding, will be seen anew, as metaphors, symbols, and invitations to a deeper truth.  And what is the source of this great reversal?  Look back, and the history of the faith unwinds like a scroll, unrolling the tale of a people, the Jews, who, in the distant past, knew only the stark, unvarnished truth of the One God, the authority of the Hebrew scriptures, and the tremulous fear of the divine.  A people divided, a people in disarray, the Pharisees, the Sadducees, the Essenes, the Zealots, and the rest, each with their own vision, their own interpretation, their own truth.  But in the end, it is not the multiplicity of voices that will prevail, but the singularity of the message, the unyielding truth of the Gospel, stripped bare of the ornamentation of time.

The abyss that lies at the heart of humanity yawns open like a chasm, a void of avarice and self-regard that consumes all in its path. The Jungle, a testament to this desolate truth, lays bare the callousness of a society that prizes gold above all else, its people reduced to mere pawns in a game of unyielding progress.
